=> when we create a repository interface that extends JpaRepository, CrudRepository, or PagingAndSortingRepository, Spring automatically finds it and creates an implementation at runtime. @Repository then?
It is mainly about exception translation. If something goes wrong in the database (like a SQLException (persistence)), @Repository tells Spring to wrap it into a generic DataAccessException. This way,
the error handling stays consistent. It does not handle the exception, it translates them to spring exception.
For instance, DataIntegrityViolationException → duplicate key
              EmptyResultDataAccessException → no data found

