=> gRPC is an RPC framework that uses HTTP/2 as its underlying transport protocol over TCP. It relies on a .proto contract to generate client and server stubs. During execution, the client serializes 
requests using Protocol Buffers and sends them over a persistent HTTP/2 connection, which gRPC manages using TCP underneath. The server receives, processes, and responds using the same mechanism.

=> In gRPC microservices, service discovery is handled externally (like Kubernetes or Consul) to locate service instances, while load balancing is typically client-side, where the gRPC client distributes 
requests across available instances using policies like round-robin over HTTP/2 connections.

=> In production systems, we avoid direct many-to-many mappings and instead introduce an explicit join entity (like Enrollment) because it allows us to store relationship attributes, improves maintainability, 
avoids hidden join tables, and gives better control over lifecycle, performance, and schema evolution.

=> mappedBy defines the inverse side of a bidirectional relationship. It tells Hibernate that the relationship is already mapped and owned by another entity field, so this side should not manage the foreign key 
or schema. Only the owning side updates the database.

class Course {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "course")
    List<Enrollment> enrollments;
}

class Enrollment {
    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "course_id") // owns relationship
    Course course;
}

If we remove mappedBy, Hibernate cannot identify the owning side of the relationship. This often results in creation of an additional join table, redundant mappings, inconsistent updates, and unpredictable 
behavior in cascading and schema generation. mappedBy is essential to ensure a single source of truth for the association.

The owning side is the entity that contains the foreign key column in the database. Only the owning side is responsible for updating the relationship in the database.
Updating the inverse side only does NOT persist changes. Only the owning side controls the database foreign key.

